# env.example — the secrets pattern
#
# HOW THIS WORKS (read once):
# - This file lists the NAMES of secrets your app needs, with NO real values.
# - It IS committed to git (it's safe — no real secrets here).
# - Your REAL values go in a file called `.env.local` (or `.env`) that is
#   git-ignored and NEVER committed.
# - In your hosting provider (Vercel etc.), set the same names+real values in
#   the Environment Variables settings — separately for Preview and Production.
# - Your code reads these from the environment, e.g. process.env.DATABASE_URL —
#   it never has the real value typed in.
#
# SETUP IN A NEW PROJECT:
#   1. Copy this file to `.env.local` and fill in real values there.
#   2. Make sure `.gitignore` contains `.env*` (so .env.local is never committed).
#   3. Add the same names+values in your hosting dashboard for Preview AND Production.
#
# RULE: if it's a secret, it lives here as a NAME only. Real values go in
# .env.local and the hosting dashboard — never in code, never committed.

# --- Examples (rename / delete to match your app) ---

# Database connection string
DATABASE_URL=

# Auth provider keys (e.g. Clerk, Auth0, Supabase Auth)
AUTH_SECRET=
AUTH_CLIENT_ID=

# Any third-party / external API key your app uses as a client
EXTERNAL_API_KEY=

# Public values (safe for the browser) are conventionally prefixed, e.g. NEXT_PUBLIC_*
# Only put NON-secret values in public vars. A secret with a PUBLIC prefix is a leak.
NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL=
